    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-06-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-06-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="729"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d729">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 165.105/982</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-06-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 5, 1916, noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 2.30 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4420. As I was on the point of presenting your 3381 [3380], received here June 1,
                    I received the following note dated June 2:</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>I have the honour to acknowledge the receipt of the memorandum which your
                        excellency communicated to this Department on May 26 relating to the
                        shipment of German dyestuffs to the United States, and beg leave in reply to
                        point out that during the negotiations which took place last year no mention
                        whatever was made either of 15,000 tons of materials nor of $5,000,000 and I
                        much regret that the offer made in April 1915, not having been taken
                        advantage of, must be considered to [have] lapsed as has already been
                        intimated to the United States Government through His Majesty’s Ambassador
                        at Washington.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Under the circumstances I will await your further instructions before taking the
                    matter up further with the Foreign Office.</p>
                <closer>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
